# Fluff Date: 2026-03-03 21:44:47
<overview>
<p>The Carnivore Assault Tank is an eighty-ton tracked combat vehicle commissioned by Clan Wolf in 3082 as part of a crash program to rebuild the Wolf Touman following the liberation of Terra. Though the Jihad exacted a heavy toll on all Coalition forces, the Wolves recognized that armored vehicles offered a faster and cheaper path to restored combat strength than waiting for new BattleMech production lines to come online. W-7 Facilities on Weingarten received the contract, with scientists directed to maximize component reuse from existing platforms while still producing an effective combat machine. The result is a long-range fire support platform built around twin Gauss rifles and extended-range medium lasers, striking a practical balance between raw firepower and logistical simplicity. Early evaluations from test units indicated the Carnivore succeeded on both counts, though Clan warriors continued to regard armored vehicles with considerably less esteem than BattleMechs or aerospace fighters.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Carnivore is powered by a 320 XL fusion engine, providing cruising and flank speeds of forty-three and sixty-four kilometers per hour respectively. While not exceptional for an eighty-ton vehicle, its performance compares favorably to many designs of similar mass. The hull mounts Advanced/3 composite armor, which offers slightly less peak protection than ferro-fibrous compounds but is cheaper to manufacture and imposes fewer space constraints on the vehicle's interior. A CASE system is integrated to improve crew survivability in the event of a catastrophic ammunition detonation.</p><p>Two Series II Gauss Rifles form the heart of the Carnivore's offensive capability. These are the same model fitted to the Sun Cobra BattleMech, a deliberate procurement decision that simplified logistics by consolidating the supply chain. With excellent range and hard-hitting kinetics, the rifles give the tank a reliable long-range engagement profile, though the thirty-two round ammunition supply demands careful fire discipline. A pair of Series 2d ER Medium Lasers supplements the main guns at intermediate ranges, providing sustained fire capability without drawing on the Gauss stockpile. Two Series XIV Heavy Machine Guns round out the armament for close-in defense against infantry. The 2SH C3 communications system incorporates an integral ECM suite, supporting network warfare and providing countermeasures against opposing electronic systems, while the Build 4 JVJ targeting and tracking system ties the weapons array together into a coherent fire control solution.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The Second Line variant strips the Carnivore to a lower-cost configuration intended for broader commercial distribution. The extralight engine is replaced by a standard fusion plant, reducing performance, and the twin Gauss rifles are replaced by a single LB-X Class 10 autocannon capable of firing both solid and cluster rounds. The heavy machine guns are downgraded to light versions and the extended-range lasers are replaced with pulse models. Despite the reduced capability, the Second Line finds buyers among second-tier customers, with the Lyran Commonwealth and Wolves-in-Exile representing the primary purchasers. Critics note little meaningful difference between the two successor-state clients these days, though both continue to procure the variant in modest numbers through the open market.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Carnivore's development traces directly to the damage the Jihad inflicted on Clan Wolf's military assets. The campaign against the Word of Blake's Protectorate and the siege of Terra cost the Wolves heavily in equipment and personnel. While the Clan hierarchy focused its rebuilding efforts on BattleMech and aerospace fighter production, practical military planners recognized that armored vehicles offered a faster and cheaper path to restored combat strength. The traditional Clan disdain for combat vehicles had long kept the armor arm underprioritized, but necessity overrode tradition in the years after 3081.</p><p>W-7 Facilities on Weingarten received the Carnivore contract with specific instructions to minimize costs and manufacturing complexity by maximizing component reuse from existing Clan Wolf platforms. The scientists involved drew the communications suite from the Ares, a Clan Wolf vehicle with an established second-line service record, and sourced the main guns from the same production run supplying the Sun Cobra. The design entered limited service in mid-3082, initially assigned to shore up frontline formations temporarily short on BattleMech assets, with the open market version following as variants became available.</p><p>Despite meeting their design objectives, Carnivore crews operated in the shadow of the Clan warrior caste's cultural hierarchy. Armor crews never commanded the battlefield respect accorded to MechWarriors or aerospace pilots, and the tank's fire support role kept it in a supporting rather than starring capacity in most engagements. That cultural ambivalence did not prevent the design from filling a genuine operational need, and the Carnivore carved out a reliable place in the Wolf Touman's order of battle through the Dark Age. The success of the basic chassis prompted development of both a trade variant for Clan Jade Falcon and a simplified second-line version for broader commercial distribution. When Weingarten passed from Clan Wolf into Clan Hell's Horses control, the Horses continued production of the Carnivore family, finding the design well-suited to their own combined-arms doctrine.</p>
</history>

